mber","topic":"Fractions, decimals, percentages","qtype":"fractions, decimals, percentages","g":"mixed","src":"0580/12/M/J/25 Q09","year":2025,"session":"MayJune","tex":"Write these fractions in order, starting with the smallest.\n$\\dfrac{5}{8}$, $\\dfrac{11}{12}$, $\\dfrac{2}{3}$, $\\dfrac{3}{4}$, $\\dfrac{13}{24}$","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"recall","cmd":"write"},{"id":"0580-2025MayJune-Paper12-Q10","paper":"2025MayJune-Paper12","qnum":10,"marks":5,"topics":["Mensuration"],"s":"5.4","d":1,"cat":"mensuration","topic":"Surface area and volume","qtype":"surface area and volume","g":"mixed","src":"0580/12/M/J/25 Q10","year":2025,"session":"MayJune","tex":"A cuboid has length 5 cm, width 2 cm and height 3 cm.\n\n(a) Draw a net of the cuboid on the 1 cm$^{2}$ grid.\n\n\\begin{InsertScreenShot}\n\n\\end{InsertScreenShot}\n\n(b) Work out the volume of the cuboid.\nGive the units of your answer.","parts":[{"label":"(a)","marks":3},{"label":"(b)","marks":2,"answer":{"type":"number","suffix":"cm³"}}],"hasFigure":true,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"draw"},{"id":"0580-2025MayJune-Paper12-Q11","paper":"2025MayJune-Paper12","qnum":11,"marks":5,"topics":["Statistics"],"s":"9.3","d":1,"cat":"statistics","topic":"Averages and measures of spread","qtype":"averages and spread","g":"mixed","src":"0580/12/M/J/25 Q11","year":2025,"session":"MayJune","tex":"For these six numbers\n0, 2, 2, 3, 4, 7\n\n(a) write down the mode\n\n(b) work out the range\n\n(c) work out the median\n\n(d) work out the mean.","parts":[{"label":"(a)","marks":1},{"label":"(b)","marks":1},{"label":"(c)","marks":1},{"label":"(d)","marks":2}],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"calculate"},{"id":"0580-2025MayJune-Paper12-Q12","paper":"2025MayJune-Paper12","qnum":12,"marks":2,"topics":["Number"],"s":"1.8","d":1,"cat":"number","topic":"Standard form","qtype":"standard form","g":"mixed","src":"0580/12/M/J/25 Q12","year":2025,"session":"MayJune","tex":"Tim has a method for multiplying a number by 99.\nHe shows his method for $53 \\times 99$.\n\n$53 \\times 99 = 53 \\times 100 - 53 = 5300 - 53 = 5247$\n\nWork out $85 \\times 99$ using Tim's method.","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"calculate"},{"id":"0580-2025MayJune-Paper12-Q13","paper":"2025MayJune-Paper12","qnum":13,"marks":6,"topics":["Geometry","Mensuration","Transformations and vectors"],"s":"4.5","d":1,"cat":"geometry","topic":"Symmetry","qtype":"symmetry","g":"mixed","src":"0580/12/M/J/25 Q13","year":2025,"session":"MayJune","tex":"(a) A quadrilateral has the geometrical properties\n\n• 4 equal length sides\n• 2 lines of symmetry\n• rotational symmetry of order 2.\n\nWrite down the mathematical name of this quadrilateral.\n\n(b) Write down two geometrical properties of a rectangle.\n\n(c) The parallel sides of a trapezium have lengths 6 cm and 4 cm.\nThe area of the trapezium is 15 cm$^{2}$.\nOn the 1 cm$^{2}$ grid, draw a trapezium with these lengths and area.\n\n\\begin{InsertScreenShot}\n\n\\end{InsertScreenShot}","parts":[{"label":"(a)","marks":1},{"label":"(b)","marks":2,"answer":{"type":"multiline","lines":2,"layout":"column","template":"____\\n____"}},{"label":"(c)","marks":3}],"hasFigure":true,"cognitive":"recall","cmd":"draw"},{"id":"0580-2025MayJune-Paper12-Q14","paper":"2025MayJune-Paper12","qnum":14,"marks":11,"topics":["Algebra and graphs","Coordinate geometry","Geometry"],"s":"2.10","d":1,"cat":"algebra","topic":"Graphs of functions","qtype":"graphs of functions","g":"function","src":"0580/12/M/J/25 Q14","year":2025,"session":"MayJune","tex":"(a) Complete the table of values for $y = (x + 3)(x - 2)$.\n\n\\begin{InsertScreenShot}\n\n\\end{InsertScreenShot}\n\n(b) On the grid, draw the graph of $y = (x + 3)(x - 2)$ for $-4 \\leq x \\leq 3$.\n\n\\begin{InsertScreenShot}\n\n\\end{InsertScreenShot}\n\n(c) Write down the coordinates of the lowest point of the graph.\n\n(d) Write down the equation of the line of symmetry of the graph.\n\n(e) Use your graph to solve the equation $(x + 3)(x - 2) = 3$.","parts":[{"label":"(a)","marks":3},{"label":"(b)","marks":4},{"label":"(c)","marks":1},{"label":"(d)","marks":1},{"label":"(e)","marks":2}],"hasFigure":true,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"draw"},{"id":"0580-2025MayJune-Paper12-Q15","paper":"2025MayJune-Paper12","qnum":15,"marks":2,"topics":["Number"],"s":"1.6","d":1,"cat":"number","topic":"The four operations","qtype":"four operations","g":"mixed","src":"0580/12/M/J/25 Q15","year":2025,"session":"MayJune","tex":"Beth thinks of a positive number, $n$.\nShe squares $n$ then subtracts 55.\nThe answer is 9.\nWork out the value of $n$.","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"calculate"},{"id":"0580-2025MayJune-Paper12-Q16","paper":"2025MayJune-Paper12","qnum":16,"marks":8,"topics":["Coordinate geometry","Mensuration","Transformations and vectors"],"s":"3.1","d":1,"cat":"coord","topic":"Coordinates","qtype":"coordinates reading/plotting","g":"graph","src":"0580/12/M/J/25 Q16","year":2025,"session":"MayJune","tex":"The diagram shows a point P and three triangles, A, B and C, on a 1 cm$^{2}$ grid.\n\n\\begin{InsertScreenShot}\n\n\\end{InsertScreenShot}\n\n(a) Find the area of triangle B.\n\n(b) (i) (c) Write down the coordinates of point P.\n\n(d) Work out the coordinates of point P after a translation by the vector $\\begin{pmatrix} -20 \\\\ 12 \\end{pmatrix}$.\n\n(e) Draw the image of triangle A after a reflection in the line $y = -1$.\n\n(f) Describe fully the single transformation that maps\n(i) (g) triangle A onto triangle B\n\n(h) triangle A onto triangle C.","parts":[{"label":"(a)","marks":1,"answer":{"type":"number","suffix":"cm²"}},{"label":"(b)","marks":0},{"label":"(c)","marks":1},{"label":"(d)","marks":1},{"label":"(e)","marks":2},{"label":"(f)","marks":0},{"label":"(g)","marks":3},{"label":"(h)","marks":3}],"hasFigure":true,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"describe"},{"id":"0580-2025MayJune-Paper12-Q17","paper":"2025MayJune-Paper12","qnum":17,"marks":2,"topics":["Number"],"s":